00:32:15.500 --> 00:32:16.970
Another African story.

00:32:16.970 --> 00:32:19.050
So if comes back.

00:32:19.050 --> 00:32:21.500
It comes back and it multiplies.

00:32:21.500 --> 00:32:24.500
LIESL TOMMY: I want to also add,
because I feel like both of you

00:32:24.500 --> 00:32:26.690
asked versions of
the same question,

00:32:26.690 --> 00:32:29.190
and it's a question that comes
up again and again and again.

00:32:29.190 --> 00:32:31.920
Which is, how do we make
space for ourselves?

00:32:31.920 --> 00:32:38.230
And, you know, I had a similar
parent situation as Lupita.

00:32:38.230 --> 00:32:40.900
Which is that my
father was a Marxist,

00:32:40.900 --> 00:32:42.630
so it was very hard core.

00:32:46.860 --> 00:32:49.290
But what he always
said is, you do not

00:32:49.290 --> 00:32:52.430
let the dominant culture
tell you who you are

00:32:52.430 --> 00:32:54.740
or what your culture is.

00:32:54.740 --> 00:32:56.716
They've got nothing
to do with you.

00:32:56.716 --> 00:32:58.860
You ultimately will
be teaching them.

00:32:58.860 --> 00:33:02.360
And here's an example, cause
I feel like we've sort of been

00:33:02.360 --> 00:33:03.370
saying, just do it.

00:33:03.370 --> 00:33:06.780
But there are
practical questions

00:33:06.780 --> 00:33:08.420
around how do you just do it?

00:33:08.420 --> 00:33:13.100
So for example, I'm working on
a project at Disney right now.

00:33:13.100 --> 00:33:14.370
And it's a big project.

00:33:14.370 --> 00:33:17.530
It's got about a
$28 million budget.

00:33:17.530 --> 00:33:20.000
They've probably never
hired a woman of color

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:23.180
to helm a project like that.

00:33:23.180 --> 00:33:25.760
The first thing I did
was hire an entire design

00:33:25.760 --> 00:33:28.180
and creative team who are
basically people of color.

00:33:28.180 --> 00:33:30.540
They've never seen that before.

00:33:30.540 --> 00:33:35.430
Choreographer, set
designer, costume designer,

00:33:35.430 --> 00:33:37.430
music director,
all people of color

00:33:37.430 --> 00:33:38.660
because this is what I do.

00:33:38.660 --> 00:33:42.510
I think it's my job to advocate
for women and people of color,

00:33:42.510 --> 00:33:45.520
because I don't know
who else will, right?

00:33:45.520 --> 00:33:46.870
So that's the first thing.

00:33:46.870 --> 00:33:49.740
I don't ask for
permission, you just do it.

00:33:49.740 --> 00:33:52.430
And then the next thing
was, I started advocating

00:33:52.430 --> 00:33:54.590
for diversity in casting.

00:33:54.590 --> 00:33:56.710
And I didn't ask permission.

00:33:56.710 --> 00:33:59.620
The first presentation in front
of Bob Iger and Tom Staggs,

00:33:59.620 --> 00:34:02.610
you know, there were just
people of color there.

00:34:02.610 --> 00:34:04.980
And I could see that
people were startled,

00:34:04.980 --> 00:34:08.770
because with Disney it's really
about the precise re-creation

00:34:08.770 --> 00:34:11.679
of a film.

00:34:11.679 --> 00:34:13.500
And there was a
lot of discussion.

00:34:13.500 --> 00:34:16.170
I never got permission
because people were too

00:34:16.170 --> 00:34:18.080
nervous to actually say yes.

00:34:18.080 --> 00:34:20.592
And then as we moved
through the gates

00:34:20.592 --> 00:34:22.050
I just kept pushing
it to the point

00:34:22.050 --> 00:34:25.780
where now I have princesses
playing leads who

00:34:25.780 --> 00:34:29.699
are white people on camera
but, in our production,

00:34:29.699 --> 00:34:32.850
they're all people of color.

00:34:32.850 --> 00:34:36.850
So you can't-- you just
have to forge ahead.

00:34:36.850 --> 00:34:40.570
Trust your instincts
and, as Danai said,

00:34:40.570 --> 00:34:44.210
you have to enact your mission.

00:34:44.210 --> 00:34:47.340
Because if the
work is undeniable,

00:34:47.340 --> 00:34:49.790
it doesn't matter
what people look like,

00:34:49.790 --> 00:34:51.570
or what their sex is.

00:34:51.570 --> 00:34:54.070
They're going to respond
to the work, right?

00:34:54.070 --> 00:34:55.980
But if you ask
permission, or if you

00:34:55.980 --> 00:34:58.090
think their rules
are your rules,

00:34:58.090 --> 00:35:00.710
you're going to be screwed.

00:35:00.710 --> 00:35:02.530
AKOSUA BUSIA: I'm so
glad Liesl said that.

00:35:02.530 --> 00:35:06.970
Because I grabbed the mic from
Danai, because I don't want

00:35:06.970 --> 00:35:09.000
it to be left out, which
you just addressed.

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:12.140
There is a financial
reality to all of this,

00:35:12.140 --> 00:35:13.890
and unless you have
people like this--

00:35:13.890 --> 00:35:17.380
because this play is
put on by the only two

00:35:17.380 --> 00:35:19.510
black producers on Broadway.

00:35:19.510 --> 00:35:22.170
And that is Alia Jones
and Stephen Byrd.

00:35:22.170 --> 00:35:26.380
And there's a reality that,
who is going to take the risk,

00:35:26.380 --> 00:35:29.300
as they call it,
and back something?

00:35:29.300 --> 00:35:31.390
And it's generally
people of color

00:35:31.390 --> 00:35:34.050
that will back people of
color, or they'll forget.

00:35:34.050 --> 00:35:36.590
You know I had said this
before that, Lupita,

00:35:36.590 --> 00:35:40.370
she was asked to do
something at the public.

00:35:40.370 --> 00:35:43.930
And she chose this from
having done it at Yale.

00:35:43.930 --> 00:35:47.380
And her star power
made them go, OK.

00:35:47.380 --> 00:35:49.090
And then you get
producers who say,

00:35:49.090 --> 00:35:52.220
I'll take the risk on that,
because other people won't.

00:35:52.220 --> 00:35:55.600
Most of the Trip to
Bountifuls, and all

00:35:55.600 --> 00:35:57.670
that, you've seen
on Broadway have

00:35:57.670 --> 00:36:00.770
been by a production
team who are black.

00:36:00.770 --> 00:36:03.620
I did a film years ago
called The Color Purple.

00:36:03.620 --> 00:36:06.980
And Alice Walker and Quincy
Jones said a certain amount,

00:36:06.980 --> 00:36:11.160
I think it was 50% or 60%
of the crew had to be black.

00:36:11.160 --> 00:36:14.210
Now a lot of that crew
were not unionized,

00:36:14.210 --> 00:36:19.080
had to get unionized, and have
been working on top, top films

00:36:19.080 --> 00:36:19.970
ever since.

00:36:19.970 --> 00:36:23.060
With the big name directors
because they named--

00:36:23.060 --> 00:36:24.390
they worked with Spielberg.

00:36:24.390 --> 00:36:28.240
Now they didn't get their
talent from working,

00:36:28.240 --> 00:36:30.760
they got their
chance from someone

00:36:30.760 --> 00:36:34.130
who wrote a book, and someone
who has the power to say,

00:36:34.130 --> 00:36:37.110
this is what I need when
you're doing this project.

00:36:37.110 --> 00:36:39.140
So there's also that reality.

00:36:39.140 --> 00:36:41.590
And I'm an artist, and
an artist at heart.

00:36:41.590 --> 00:36:44.440
So we love to just be
artists and, you know,

00:36:44.440 --> 00:36:46.880
and you feel that--
finally my art.

00:36:46.880 --> 00:36:50.830
But there's a financial reality.

00:36:50.830 --> 00:36:52.312
And you have to
have that backing.

00:36:52.312 --> 00:36:53.270
DANAI GURIRA: And yeah.

00:36:53.270 --> 00:36:54.617
Just to throw in there also.

00:36:54.617 --> 00:36:55.700
I've heard this sometimes.

00:36:55.700 --> 00:36:57.050
Go where you're loved.

00:36:57.050 --> 00:36:59.710
Sometimes people are-- they want
to go where-- what about them?

00:36:59.710 --> 00:37:00.710
What about that theater?

00:37:00.710 --> 00:37:01.690
What about those folk?

00:37:01.690 --> 00:37:02.700
Go where your loved.

00:37:02.700 --> 00:37:04.260
It might not be
where you expected,

00:37:04.260 --> 00:37:07.140
but they're-- the people who
appreciate your voice are going

00:37:07.140 --> 00:37:08.960
to stand underneath it and help.

00:37:08.960 --> 00:37:12.490
The theaters that helped us
create and develop this play

00:37:12.490 --> 00:37:14.250
will always be a part
of what it's become.

00:37:14.250 --> 00:37:16.910
Because they loved
us, we went there,

00:37:16.910 --> 00:37:18.270
and we were able to nurture it.

00:37:18.270 --> 00:37:22.330
And so it might not always be
where you expect, but don't

00:37:22.330 --> 00:37:24.810
always look at that, I want
that, it might be that,

00:37:24.810 --> 00:37:27.244
and that it's great because
they believe in your voice.

00:37:27.244 --> 00:37:28.160
BONITA STEWART: Great.

